body:
I put this code the following code in test.pyx.

```
ctypedef struct TestType:
    char string[10]

cdef f(const TestType *x):
    cdef const char *y = x.string
```

Then I compiled it with `cython test.pyx -o test.c && gcc -I /usr/include/python3.6m/ -lpython3.6m test.c -shared -fPIC -Wall -o test.so`.

x.string is an array behind a const pointer, so it becomes a `const char *`, which is then assigned to a `const char *` variable. The equivalent C code compiles without warnings unless you remove const from the variable (except for y being unused):

```
struct TestType {
    char string[10];
};

void f(const struct TestType *x) {
    const char *y = x->string;
}
```

This was compiled with `gcc test2.c -shared -fPIC -Wall -o test2.so`.

However, in the C code generated by Cython, the pointer if first assigned to an intermediate value (`__pyx_t_1`), which is declared as `char *`, which triggers a discarded-qualifiers warning.

This was done with Cython 0.27.3 and GCC 7.5.0
